    "reasoning": "First, solve the functional equation $ f(x f(x) + 2y) = f(x^2) + f(y) + x + y - 1 $. Assume $ f $ is affine: $ f(x) = mx + b $. Substituting into the equation and equating coefficients gives $ m = 1 $ and $ b = 1 $, so $ f(x) = x + 1 $. Analyzing at $ x = 0 $ yields $ f(2y) = f(y) + y $, which for the affine solution confirms $ m = 1 $. Thus, $ a = 1 $, so $ k = a + 8 = 9 $.\n\nNext, consider the game on $ k = 9 $ cells. To maximize moves, all type 1 moves must add $ 2^0 = 1 $ (maximizing $ M_1 $). The total mass (sum of all numbers) must equal $ 2^n $, requiring $ M_1 = 2^n $ type 1 moves. Each type 2 move combines two equal numbers, reducing cell count by 1. Starting from 0 cells and ending at 1 cell, $ M_1 - M_2 = 1 \\implies M_2 = M_1 - 1 $. Total moves: $ M = M_1 + M_2 = 2^{n+1} - 1 $. With $ k = 9 \\geq 2 $, the cell constraint is always satisfied by interleaving additions and combinations, confirming the maximum moves.",
    "answer": "2^{n+1} - 1"
}
